If you exceed your query limits the API returns a 429 (Too Many Requests) and details about the limit breach.

- Monthly query limit (example):
  - HTTP 429 with body:
    {
      "success": false,
      "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
      "usage": {
        "current": 101,
        "max": 100,
        "exceeded": true,
        "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
      }
    }

- Per‑minute / short‑term rate limit:
  - HTTP 429 with an error like:
    {
      "error": {
        "code": "RATE_LIMIT_EXCEEDED",
        "message": "Rate limit exceeded. Try again in 60 seconds"
      }
    }

Responses also include X-RateLimit headers (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset) so clients can see remaining quota and when it resets.

Recommended handling: check the headers, implement exponential backoff on 429, cache/reduce duplicate queries, batch requests, or upgrade your plan.

When a user exceeds their monthly query limit the API returns an HTTP 429 Too Many Requests response with rate-limit details. The response includes an error message and a `usage` object showing current usage, max allowed, whether it’s exceeded, and the monthly reset time. Example:

{
  "success": false,
  "error": "Monthly query limit exceeded",
  "usage": {
    "current": 101,
    "max": 100,
    "exceeded": true,
    "reset_at": "2026-02-01T00:00:00Z"
  }
}

Rate-limit headers (X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, X-RateLimit-Reset) are also included. You must wait until the reset time or upgrade your plan to continue.

